<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: MOORPARK; TACO BELL, PIZZA HUT COMING TO COLLEGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two fast-food traditions are making their way to Moorpark College. 
</P>
<P>
 Food service officials at the community college have signed contracts to 
operate small Pizza Hut and Taco Bell franchises inside the cafeteria. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are sort of following the models of other colleges and universities," said 
Bud Bailey, food services supervisor at Moorpark College. "The four-year 
schools have been doing it for some time." 
</P>
<P>
 Bailey said a survey conducted last May indicated that Moorpark College 
students and employees would patronize fast-food outlets such as Taco Bell and 
Pizza Hut. 
</P>
<P>
 The arrangement calls for Moorpark College to keep 90% of the receipts and 
forward the remainder to the two corporations, which in exchange will provide 
sales guidance, training and advertising. 
</P>
<P>
 The cafeteria grossed almost $400,000 in revenue last year, Bailey said. But 
Taco Bell and Pizza Hut officials told him to expect an increase this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "The residual effect (Taco Bell) claims is 15% additional business for the 
cafeteria as a whole," Bailey said. "They project a 15% increase just because 
it's there." 
</P>
<P>
 Bailey expects to hire three additional students for part-time work as a 
result of the fast-food kiosks, which are scheduled to open before the end of 
the month. 
</P>
<P>
 There will be no ordering at either of the outlets, Bailey said. Customers 
will be able to select tacos, burritos and pizzas from a countertop and pay for 
their food within minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's designed to be a grab-and-go arrangement," Bailey said. JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</TEXT>
