<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: STUDENTS GO BY THE BOOK IN SAFETY PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Under a backdrop of children drawing on coloring books filled with safety 
messages, school and law enforcement officials announced a new program Thursday 
that seeks to help keep youngsters safe at school. 
</P>
<P>
 The United Way-sponsored effort, called Play it Safe, provides thousands of 
the books to Ventura County's school-age children, and educators and public 
safety authorities hope they will teach children to watch out for trouble. 
</P>
<P>
 "More than simply a picture in a coloring book, each drawing is a springboard 
that can lead parents and children into a discussion," Dist. Atty. Michael D. 
Bradbury said at announcement ceremonies at the Ventura County Government 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
 Bradbury was joined by a host of school superintendents and United Way 
organizers in announcing the Play it Safe campaign, which began by distributing 
more than 50,000 of the coloring books to area students. 
</P>
<P>
 Eugene Junette, a former aerospace industry manager who founded Play it Safe 
International in 1974, told the administrators that giving children an 
opportunity to draw pictures of safety lessons helps reinforce the message. 
</P>
<P>
 Junette said the group, which is spending $9,000 in United Way funds to pay 
for the books, began when a group of parents formed to make schools a safer 
environment for children. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had 19,922 coloring books when we started," he said. "Today we have more 
than 26.5 million in 61 countries." 
</P>
<P>
 United Way spokesman David Menchaca said the effort would branch out to older 
children later this school year. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're looking to develop into the upper-grade levels by bringing law 
enforcement agencies to the school districts to discuss safety," Menchaca said. 
"We want to bring in those people that have been involved in gangs and violence 
and troubles with the law to discuss a better way of life for youth." 
</P>
<P>
 Thirteen-year-old Jim Murdoch, a student at Cabrillo Middle School in Ventura, 
said trouble on campus can happen at any time. 
</P>
<P>
 "It can get pretty violent if you say anything," he said. "They take it real 
personally. This program will help, but I'm not sure about the coloring books." 
JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</TEXT>
