<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Carlos V. Lozano 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BURGLAR ALARM: Seventeen burglaries have taken place at Ventura County fire 
stations while firefighters were away, in some cases, on false alarms (B1) . . 
. Stations in Simi Valley and Newbury Park were the latest to be hit . . . 
Worse yet, investigators suspect that the culprit may work for the Fire 
Department. Said Sgt. Harold Humphries of the Sheriff's Department: "We believe 
that it's either an ex- or a current employee." 
</P>
<P>
 ALL ABOARD?: With attendance at the Ventura County Fair down 10% this year, 
it's no surprise that ridership on Metrolink commuter trains to the fair also 
took a dive . . . Ridership dropped from 30,000 last year to about 21,000. 
Ticket sales will pay for most of the operating costs (B1) . . . the remaining 
$5,000 will be picked up by fair operators. Said one county transportation 
official: "The agreement is that we give our time, energy and support and the 
Fair Board pays the extra costs." 
</P>
<P>
 FAMOUS HILLBILLY: Let me tell you a story 'bout a man named Jed . . . Better 
yet, you can meet the man himself . . . Buddy Ebsen, who starred as Jed 
Clampett in the old television series "The Beverly Hillbillies," will be at 
Phantom Books in Ventura from 1 to 3 p.m. Sunday signing copies of his new 
autobiography, "The Other Side of Oz." . . . In his book, Ebsen recounts how he 
lost the role of the Tin Man in "The Wizard of Oz." Turns out, he nearly died 
after inhaling the aluminum dust in his makeup. 
</P>
<P>
 BEACH WALK: A group of hikers hoping to establish a California coastal trail 
will end their five-day promotional trek along Ventura County's 35-mile-long 
coastline about noon today . . . Meanwhile, the Sierra Club Singles of Ventura 
County are planning their own beach walk this Sunday from Rincon State Park to 
Carpinteria . . . Tender feet need not be discouraged. This walk is a little 
shorter -- seven miles round-trip. Said club official Carol Marsh: "This is 
more suitable for people who want an easy excursion on the weekend." 
Information: 984-9806. 
</P>
<P>
 TONIGHT: The Buds play rockin' blues at the Hungry Hunter in Thousand Oaks. 
Free. Information: 497-3925. More events, B2 
</P>
<P>
 WEATHER: Mostly sunny in the afternoon with highs to 80s. B10 
</P>
<P>
 * The Top of Today's News is on A2 
