<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; CHATS ARE SPECIAL TIMES FOR ELDERLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Once a week, Kim Weggeland meets up with a special friend to talk.  
</P>
<P>
 Their hourlong conversations are freewheeling. Weggeland might talk about her 
upcoming wedding. Her friend, an elderly woman, might discuss plans for the 
holidays. 
</P>
<P>
 The pair was brought together two months ago through a YMCA community outreach 
program that matches senior citizens with younger people. 
</P>
<P>
 Weggeland, a 31-year-old Newport Beach sales manager, said she and her match 
had an instant rapport. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's working out great," she said. "We talk about everything." 
</P>
<P>
 About a dozen senior citizens from throughout Orange County take part in the 
program. Organizers are now looking for more volunteers to spend one day a week 
with senior citizens. A training class for participants will be held Sept. 21 
in Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
 Elana Peters, a coordinator of Project Reach Out for Seniors, said lonely 
elderly people benefit from having regular visitors. 
</P>
<P>
 "It gives them something to look forward to each week," said Peters. "We find 
that many seniors are isolated. This causes depression and loneliness. I think 
this adds to their aging and (can cause them) to go downhill physically more 
quickly." 
</P>
<P>
 The program provides matches for seniors who live in homes or nursing 
facilities. 
</P>
<P>
 Both seniors and volunteers fill out questionnaires that program organizers 
use to make the matches. 
</P>
<P>
 The volunteer workshop will be at 6:30 p.m. Sept. 21 in the YMCA Community 
Counseling Services Office, Building 2, at Red Hill Avenue and Main Street in 
Irvine. For more information, call (714) 253-4140. 
</P>
<P>
 Each volunteer must be willing to spend at least an hour a week with a senior 
and stay with the program for at least six months. 
</P>
<P>
 Peters and Weggeland said volunteers also reap rewards from the service. 
</P>
<P>
 "It gives you a better sense of yourself and a better understanding of 
seniors," Peters said. SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</TEXT>
