<P>
2 FOUND DEAD AFTER NEIGHBORS CALL POLICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID HALDANE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The bodies of two elderly people who may have been dead for up to 10 days were 
found Thursday by police who had been asked to check their home. 
</P>
<P>
 Officers were held at bay by a barking dog for several hours before they could 
enter the house in the 200 block of East Wilson Street, according to Sgt. Matt 
Collett. 
</P>
<P>
 Police would not release the names of the residents or the cause of death. 
After discovering the bodies about 9:30 a.m., officers sealed the house until 
investigators could obtain a search warrant, Collett said. 
</P>
<P>
 Neighbors identified the residents as an elderly husband and wife who had 
lived in the middle-class area of single-family homes for 25 years. The 
husband, they said, was a retired Marine Corps pilot, and the couple had met 
and married in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
 The man had recently suffered a stroke and was depressed, neighbors said, and 
was scheduled to visit a medical clinic for tests on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Neighbors had called police and asked them to check on the couple. 
</P>
