<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISPLAY SPACE SHRINKS SO GIFT SHOP CAN STRETCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ZAN DUBIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If visitors to the Lun*na Menoh show get the feeling that Laguna Art Museum's 
satellite gallery in South Coast Plaza has shrunk, they'll be right. 
</P>
<P>
 The museum has reduced the gallery's floor space by half, to 600 square feet, 
to expand the adjacent gift shop. 
</P>
<P>
 The redesign was "done basically to make more profit from shop" sales, museum 
acting director Susan M. Anderson said. Like arts organizations nationwide that 
have seen private- and public-sector funding dwindle, "We are looking for new 
ways to be entrepreneurial right now," Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The redesign is not necessarily permanent. It is viewed as the "first phase of 
what we hope is a complete redesign of the space," Anderson said, which may 
lead to exhibitions that extend "into the space of the plaza itself." Plans 
also call for more functional art, such as artist-designed furniture, to be 
offered in the shop. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're hoping that, with the renovation and the new product mix, we'll bring 
more people into" the satellite, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, the museum this week announced the bequest of a contemporary art 
collection and that it has hired a temporary replacement for its recently 
resigned associate director of development. 
</P>
<P>
 The 140-piece bequest is from the trust of Richard H. Mumper, a Laguna Beach 
art collector, longtime museum member and English teacher who died in May. It 
includes works by Richard Diebenkorn, Carlos Almaraz and Billy Al Bengston, and 
is "one of the most impressive collections of contemporary art given to the 
museum in the past decade," said Bolton Colburn, the museum's curator of 
collections. 
</P>
<P>
 Jan Young is the part-time "development consultant" hired to stand in until a 
permanent replacement is found for Marilyn (Mickey) Shaw, who resigned in 
August. 
</P>
<P>
 Young, who will oversee the museum's fund-raising programs, will retain her 
other job as a marketing and development consultant to Santa Ana's Discovery 
Museum. Anderson said she expects to hire replacements soon for two other 
development staffers who resigned recently. ZAN DUBIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
