<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Bill Kohlhaase 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *** Abbey Lincoln, Hank Jones, "When There Is Love," Gitanes Jazz. Two of 
jazz's most distinct voices come together in a relaxed program that shows both 
off to advantage.Lincoln's voice, somewhat huskier than in years past, still 
retains its attractive depth and color -- spicy on "C'est Si Bon," warm and 
intimate on her own "A Part of Me." Her struggle to find pitch on "I Should 
Care" makes her delivery even more poignant. Jones, working alone on "Close 
Your Eyes," proves himself an astute spokesman, juggling rhythms and soloing in 
almost conversational tunes. "Angel Face," with words by Lincoln and music by 
Jones, is especially heavenly. 
</P>
<P>
 Albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three stars 
(good, recommended), four stars (excellent).  
</P>
<P>
 Bill Kohlhaase 
