<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; HOSPITAL 
CLINIC REOPENS; CAUSE OF ODORS INVESTIGATED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A clinic at County-USC Medical Center reopened Thursday as authorities 
searched for the cause of an odor that prompted hundreds to flee and 34 people 
to experience breathing problems and burning eyes. 
</P>
<P>
 "Some said it smelled like natural gas or bleach," said Harvey Kern, a 
spokesman for the medical center.However, natural gas was ruled out as the 
cause. 
</P>
<P>
 About 250 workers, patients and family members fled the two-story clinic after 
the odor was detected about 11 a.m. Wednesday. The clinic provides outpatient 
pediatric and family planning care. 
</P>
<P>
 Dozens of firefighters and hazardous material crews responded to the scene and 
took 34 people, including 13 hospital employees, to County-USC's main hospital 
and to three other hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
 They suffered from "mild to moderate symptoms" such as coughing, watering eyes 
and nausea, Kern said. All were treated and released. 
