<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL PREVIEW; CONTRERAS HAS RIO MESA READY TO TAKE WING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF FLETCHER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 George Contreras is a head coach again and for opponents in the Channel 
League, that can mean only one thing: 
</P>
<P>
 "Pass out the aspirin," Buena Coach Rick Scott said. 
</P>
<P>
 Contreras was promoted this season from assistant to head coach at Rio Mesa 
after John Reardon retired. He has brought in his reliable old offense, the 
Delaware Wing T. 
</P>
<P>
 "The rest of our league better hold on to their fannies because they are going 
to see some stuff that they've never seen," said Scott, who coached at Newbury 
Park when Contreras was running the Wing T at Westlake in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
 The Wing T was designed at the University of Delaware specifically to help 
physically overmatched teams compete. The Wing T calls for four players in the 
backfield: a quarterback, a fullback, a a halfback and a wingback. 
</P>
<P>
 Wing T offenses begin with confusing shifts and players in motion. "It's the 
closest thing to Canadian football that American football has," Scott said. 
After the snap, there are a series of fakes and misdirections, so no one is 
quite sure who's got the ball. 
</P>
<P>
 "There's more counters off it than Carter's got liver pills," Scott said. 
</P>
<P>
 Contreras began researching the Wing T when he took over the program at 
Westlake. In 1978, the school's first year of varsity football, Contreras had 
no seniors and needed to find a way to compete. 
</P>
<P>
 He was intrigued when he heard about the innovative offense they were running 
in Delaware and a few other places around the country. One year, Marv Levy used 
the offense with the Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was just so unusual," Contreras said. "We'd never seen anything like it, 
so we started researching it. Everything we heard about it said you don't need 
big players because everything is (based on) angles." 
</P>
<P>
 Contreras read books. He attended clinics. He watched films. He even flew to 
Delaware, where he learned he didn't quite understand the offense as well as he 
thought he did. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was watching (Delaware) practice," he said, "and I went straight to a pay 
phone and called one of my assistants and said, 'When we get back, we are 
having a staff meeting, because we have been doing this totally (wrong).' There 
are so many nuances." 
</P>
<P>
 After 11 years of running the Wing T at Westlake, there are few nuances 
Contreras doesn't know. 
</P>
<P>
 "George is the best at it," Scott said. "That's not just a pat on the back to 
one of my peers, but he is the guru. I've probably faced (the Wing T) 25-30 
times in the past 30 years, but no one runs it like him. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 "George truly knows if you take something away from him (defensively), you 
have to give something up. The only thing that can stop him is lack of talent." 
</P>
<P>
 Sometimes, not even that. 
</P>
<P>
 "One year he had a tailback that was flat out slow," Scott said, "and he still 
gained 1,000 yards." 
</P>
<P>
 Contreras ran the offense so well at Westlake that the Warriors won three 
league titles. The Wing T even spread through the Marmonte League, with Royal 
and Channel Islands adopting it. 
</P>
<P>
 Scott predicts the same might happen in the Channel League. 
</P>
<P>
 "Other teams are going to run the stuff to prepare and they are going to see 
stuff that they like," he said. "And other teams are going to run the Delaware 
just because it works for Rio Mesa." 
</P>
<P>
 With the Wing T, Rio Mesa is expected to give its opponents headaches, but the 
Spartans may still not be able to overcome teams such as league favorites 
Ventura and Santa Barbara. 
</P>
<P>
 "The bottom line," Contreras said, "is we are still going to be playing with a 
lot of sophomores and juniors with not a lot of varsity-level experience." 
